ly candidates for future orthodoxy, or as being addressed at a small, unrepresen
tative part of the mainstream.
 Because of the long time needed for ideas to move from the edge to orthodoxy,
 in their own educations heterodox economists are likely to have been exposed
 to the now-obsolete orthodoxy, became disenchanted with it, and then moved
