\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rooted in neoclassical economics and turning instead to geographical approaches
 related to various strains of heterodox economics, particularly Marxist,
 institutionalist, Keynesian, and neo-Ricardian variants 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sheppard2011geographical"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast to neoclassical economics, with its methodological individualism
 and consequent microeconomic focus on individual behavior, these heterodox
 strains emphasized societal structures, social relations, and institutions,
 leading to a more macroeconomic form of analysis.
 David Harvey's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "harvey1978theurban,harvey2006thelimits"

\end_inset

 work was extraordinarily seminal in this transformation, inspiring new
 areas in economic and urban geography, such as the geography of money and
 finance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "leyshon_limits_2004"

\end_inset

.
 On the other side, and particularly in the U.S., a small-but-prominent group
 of heterodox economists – such as Ann Markusen, Barry Bluestone, Bennett
 Harrison, David Gordon, and Matthew Edel – brought heterodox economic theory
 to bear on the concerns of urban and economic geography, and in the process
 transformed heterodox economic analysis itself by making the spatial dimension
 a fundamental component.
\end_layout

